column28: 5+ hours straight is very tiring.  That said, it is a lot better than talking on the phone for that long.
column29: I will use it as a basis for my students to learn about pathogens and vectors in context of those that can affect them.
column30: Group by Grade Level instead of tasks when appropriate.
column31: Nothing.  Long but informative.  I learned a lot that I did not understand before workshop.

column29: I plan on using the information that I learned to carry out the research with my students.  I want to use the Common Online Data Analysis Platform (CODAP) website to help my students analyze their results from this experiment and others as well.  I want to continue integrating ArcGIS into my classroom lessons as well.
column30: I think this workshop was a good balance of hands on, small group and lecture.  The only thing that was hard was being in front of the computer for so long, but due to the current situation, that was not something that could be avoided.
column31: I appreciate all that you all did to prepare this and make it as interactive as possible.  All of the sessions were great.  It took some stepping out of my comfort zone to share my screen and learn hands on with everyone watching, but I appreciate the opportunity to do that as it will help me in the future as I move forward with this project and as a teacher.

column29: Designing an investigation, intro to GIS, relating the research to several TN Sci Standards, mitigating the problem of disease transition jand communicating results of mosquito research and behavior change in the community.
column30: I would like to spend more time relating what we are doing to the TN science standards or the practices to justify the time taken away from the curriculum

column28: None, it is what it is.
column31: valuable information for me and my students- thank you

column28:
1-to-1 GIS Breakout room was very effective; however, not nearly long enough!!
Only other problem was some folks talked a lot and others did not get a chance to talk at all. The communications team breakout room was nice because someone actually realized that 1 person did not get a chance to talk and asked their opinion. So, having some equability in the conversations could be better. Maybe use a facilitator in the rooms next time?
column29: Becky's mosquito powerpoints with embedded video clips! I loved the GIS Inquiries, but don't see one for my subject. Maybe I can modify one to work.
column30: The idea of pairing up the folks with lots of GIS experience/previous coursework with the beginners was really good! However; the time to practice the 1-1 was not nearly long enough. I get much more out of something if we are all on a level playing field. So, maybe even doing more for the beginners and slow down!!!
column31: Overall very good. I may have missed the connection on Joshua Rosenberg's presentation. Not sure how the data was compiled, how it integrates with GIS and how we can use it. Is there a video tutorial for this? I am also wondering if the "attributes" (column headings) could be worded better? Meaning, that someone unfamiliar with the project could easily read the word and know exactly what data it represented. Bottom line for me is I need to spend more time playing with the GIS on my own.

column28: It’s tiring to look at a screen, but it went pretty well. I liked the breakout rooms
column29: I want to get more involved with the GIS so I am working on how to incorporate the maps into our learning more
column30: Our Friday afternoon chat needs to be on Thursday or something so that people can take it home, sit on the info, and come back fresh to discuss more the next day. I’m dead by Friday afternoon
column31: The small group GIS work was super helpful

column28: The ambiguity of the task throughout the week left the breakout rooms rather unproductive.

column29: Involving students in writing their own hypothesis, collecting data, study of populations
Each presenter contributed real-world tools and content that students could deem interesting and applicable.....communication, career/job, and science behind the project......
column30: If Covid19 is still raging on, perhaps there is a covered outdoor facility that could be used that could get us outside but socially distanced...... (for the summer PD's....) :)
column31: Presenters, as well as the PD leaders, are extremely informed with their subject matter as well as empathetic to classroom teachers (ing).
